  "prompt": "In Bhagavad Gita 18th chapter, Lord Krishna says \"Arjuna is his dearest friend\". I am curious to know if there are any stories in Arjuna's previous birth, to become Lord's dearest friend in Vishnu's incarnation as Krishna?",
  "response": "Yes, there are indeed stories in Hindu mythology that explain the bond between Lord Krishna and Arjuna, tracing their relationship to previous births. One of the most well-known stories comes from the Mahabharata and some Puranic texts, which narrate how Arjuna and Krishna are linked through their past lives.\n\nIn one such story, it is mentioned that in a previous birth, Arjuna was a great sage named Nara, and Lord Vishnu was his companion, the sage Narayana. The two sages took a vow to help humanity and took incarnations whenever there was a great need in the world. Their friendship was characterized by deep mutual respect and loyalty.\n\nAnother popular story comes from the time of the previous incarnation of Krishna, where he is believed to have taken birth as the son of Vasudeva and Devaki. In that past life, it is said that Arjuna had been a prince named Partha who had dedicated his life to spiritual practice and Dharma. Their goodness and piety in various incarnations established a strong bond of friendship.\n\nThe nature of their friendship is so profound that, in the Bhagavad Gita, Krishna expresses that Arjuna is not only his friend but also a part of his own self, indicating a deeply spiritual connection that transcends ordinary relationships.\n\nThese stories highlight the significance of dharma (righteousness) and the eternal relationship between divine beings and their devotees, with Krishna's guidance and Arjuna's commitment leading to their ultimate spiritual evolution together.",
